\subsection*{Useful facts and assumptions}
\vspace{-2.8ex}

    \begin{compactitem}

        \item After consulting some experts on algae growth under terrestrial
        conditions, your team has selected a few organisms for cultivation.
        They all have about the same nutritional, temperature, and pH requirements,
        which are not expected to change much in a space environment. Thus
        your team has decided to ignore these factors in the modeling process.


        \item The algae biologists gave you some formulas about algae growth,
        but the notes from the
        meeting were lost, and you weren't too sure you understood all of it
        anyway. However, you do remember that they said that you can get
        modestly good estimates using dimensional analysis.%, if you remember
        % that unlike many scenarios you have trained on, this situation
        % requires a constant that carries dimensions: namely, $[K] = L^8
        % M^{-2} \Theta^{-1}$. You hope to estimate this constant from the data
        % you have.

        \item Lacking a more sophisticated model, your team agrees that
        dimensional analysis might help in determining an expression for the
        daily mass of algae available for harvest, $M$, in terms of the
        concentration of nutrients, $\rho$, and other important quantities.

        \item Since the algae must be grown in the space habitat, there is a fixed
        surface area available, about \SI{1000}{m^2}. This needs to feed 36 people,
        each of whom requires an average of \SI{1.8}{kg} algae each day.

        \item You are convinced that the other important quantities are
        the rate, $F$, at which solar energy is  delivered to the algae pond
        surface and the depth of the algae pond, $d$. The depth of the pond
        can't exceed \SI{\spacedee}{cm} in the habitat.

        %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% DIMENSIONAL ANALYSIS FORMULAS %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
        %
        %
        % g/day = k * (g/L)^a * (W/m^2)^b * m^c
        % write t = T^{-1}
        % Mt = k (Ml^3)^a (Mt^3)^b L^c
        % Mt = k M^(a+b) L^(c-3a) T^(-3b)
        % b = 1/3, a = 2/3, c = 2

        \item Many companies and government organizations are interested in
        algae cultivation on Earth, so some data are easily available. Your
        team has found an example of an algae pond in which each square meter
        of surface area yielded \SI{\earthemm}{g} of edible algae biomass each day
        with a nutrient density of \SI{\earthrho}{g/m^3}. We can go up to \SI{\spacerho}{g/m^3} in
        the space habitat.

        \item That rate of algae production was achieved in a pond with an
        average depth of \SI{\earthdee}{cm} and solar energy delivery of about
        \SI{\eartheff}{W/m^2}. In space, energy delivery is greater: about
        \SI{\spaceeff}{W/m^2}.

        \item If the in-habitat pond is not sufficent for the production of algae
        to maintain the colony of 36 people, then additional spacecraft must
        be built and launched. The fixed costs of doing this are around
        \SI{60}[\$]{} million, with an additional cost of \SI{2.2}[\$]{} million
        per square meter of pond surface.

    \end{compactitem}

\newpage

    Your team must now pull together all of its ideas to calculate an estimate
    of the available algae capacity. If additional capacity is required, your
    report should estimate its cost. You should report all answers with three
    significant digits. Once you finish your calculations, your team should
    write a professional report restating the problem and summarizing your
    work and your findings. The mission of the colonists is critical and
    obtaining sufficient funding is imperative. A rough report just won't do.
    Thus, your report must contain at least one meaningful, carefully labeled
    graph that adds something to the argument your team is making.

